record_data.record_plain_text: TARIFF West Penn Power Company d/b/a/ Allegheny Power assents to and concurs with the tariff described below, which the Monongahela Power Company filed on September 17, 2010, as such tariff is amended from time to time. Tariff Designation: Allegheny Power Open Access Transmission Tariff, Third Revised Volume No. 5

West Penn 2022 Consolidated Agreement
1
2022 CONSOLIDATED AGREEMENT
WHEREAS, on February 24, 2011, the Pennsylvania Public Utility Commission
("Commission" or “PaPUC”) approved the merger of FirstEnergy Corp. ("FirstEnergy") and Allegheny
Energy, Inc. ("AE"), under which AE would become a subsidiary of FirstEnergy ("FE-AE Merger");
and
WHEREAS, FirstEnergy is the parent company of Metropolitan Edison Company ("Met-Ed"),
Pennsylvania Electric Company ("Penelec") and West Penn Power Company ("West Penn"); and
WHEREAS, Mid-Atlantic Interstate Transmission, LLC (“MAIT”) is a subsidiary of FirstEnergy
that owns and operates certain electric facilities used for the transmission of wholesale electric energy
(MAIT, Met-Ed, Penelec, and West Penn collectively, with FirstEnergy, “FE”); and
WHEREAS, Met-Ed, Penelec, West Penn, and MAIT deliver, either directly or indirectly,
electricity to member cooperatives of the Pennsylvania Rural Electric Association ("PREA'') and
Allegheny Electric Cooperative, Inc. ("AEC") (PREA/AEC collectively, with FE, the "Parties"); and
WHEREAS, PREA/AEC and its member cooperatives are dependent upon the combined FE
system for electric delivery service to at least 225 PREA/AEC delivery points; and
WHEREAS, PREA/AEC desires to ensure reliable delivery service to its delivery points for the
foreseeable future; and
WHEREAS, FE desires to provide and enhance reliable delivery service to the PREA/AEC
delivery points; and
WHEREAS, PREA/AEC and FE recognize that FE has historically made significant investment
in its transmission and distribution infrastructure, including for projects and maintenance devoted to
circuits that both serve FE customers and have an impact on service to PREA/AEC, and that the amounts
set forth below are consistent with recent levels of expenditures; and
WHEREAS, FE and PREA/AEC worked cooperatively to consolidate into one document the
operative terms, conditions, and commitments contained within the following agreements between the
Parties following consummation of the FE-AE Merger ("2014 Consolidated Agreement"): a) the Joint
Petition For Full Settlement of the Restructuring Plans of Metropolitan Edison and Pennsylvania Electric
Company and Related Dockets and Related Court Proceedings at Commission Docket Nos. R-00974008
and R-00974009 dated September 23, 1998 ("Restructuring Agreement"); b) the Joint Petition for
Settlement of Proceeding in Investigation of Metropolitan Edison Company, Pennsylvania Electric
Company and Pennsylvania Power Company Reliability Performance at Commission Docket No. 1-
00040102 dated September 29, 2004; c) the Joint Petition for Settlement by Metropolitan Edison
Company, Pennsylvania Electric Company and Pennsylvania Power Company's Petition to Amend
Recomputed Benchmarks for Electric Distribution Reliability at Commission Docket No. P-00042115
dated December 8, 2005; d) the PREA/AEC Settlement Agreement dated November 4, 2005 clarifying
prior agreements between the Parties related to Commission Docket Nos. R-00974008 and I-00040102;
e) the PREA/AEC Settlement Agreement dated February 21, 2006; f) the PREA/AEC Settlement
2
Agreement dated August 25, 2006 related to Commission Docket No. R-00061366; g) the letter dated
January 29, 2008 from Vince Kaminski to Scott Johnson regarding the Reliability Standard Adjustment
for the Hollenback delivery point; h) the Agreement dated October 25, 2010 and subsequent Joint Petition
for Partial Settlement related to the FE-AE Merger; and i) the GPU Energy, Allegheny Electric
Cooperative, Inc., Pennsylvania Rural Electric Association - Agreement on Joint Principles on Reliability
and Reliability Standards for Cooperative Delivery Points Served via the GPU Energy Delivery System
dated March 8, 1999; and
WHEREAS, on November 24, 2014, the Parties entered into a Settlement Agreement (“2014
Extension Agreement”), in connection with FE’s August 2014 rate filings at Commission Docket Nos. R2014-2428745 (Met-Ed), R-2014-2428743 (Penelec), and R-2014-2428742 (West Penn), to extend and
modify the Joint Petition Process (“JPP”) initially started under the PaPUC Dockets Nos. R-00974008 and
R-00974009, as amended by subsequent proceedings, for five years so that the JPP would be in place
through 2022; and
WHEREAS, AEC is party to separate Amended and Restated Wheeling and Supplemental Power
Agreements (“WASP Agreements”) dated as of August 5, 2021 with Penelec, Met-Ed, and Jersey Central
Power and Light Company (“JCP&L”), which are designated respectively as Service Agreement Nos.
4222, 4223, and 4221 under the PJM Tariff and filed with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission
(“FERC”); and
WHEREAS, the WASP Agreements, among other things, govern interconnection and coordinated
operation of the Parties’ systems and Allegheny’s use of certain distribution facilities to enable Allegheny
to serve its wholesale loads; and
WHEREAS, FE has provided to AEC notice of termination of the WASP Agreements as of
October 1, 2022; and
WHEREAS, the Parties have agreed to again extend the JPP initially started under Commission
Docket Nos. R-00974008 and R-00974009, as amended by subsequent proceedings, for ten years so that
the JPP will be in place through planning year 2032 (for the 2033 construction year) as a part of a
comprehensive resolution of issues that could be raised in connection with the termination of the WASP
Agreements; and
WHEREAS, as part of the 2014 Consolidated Agreement, 2014 Extension Agreement, and
subsequent discussions in 2022 to again extend the JPP, FE and PREA/AEC agreed to work cooperatively
to consolidate into this document (“2022 Consolidated Agreement”) the operative terms, conditions and
commitments contained within the 2014 Consolidated Agreement, 2014 Extension Agreement, and the
results of their 2022 negotiations; and
NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises herein, FirstEnergy,
on its own behalf and on behalf of Met-Ed, Penelec, West Penn, and MAIT, and PREA/AEC, on behalf
of itself and of its member cooperatives, hereby enter into this 2022 Consolidated Agreement to restate
the obligations and rights of the Parties and agree as follows:
3
A. General Terms
1. The Parties acknowledge and agree that FE shall adhere to the retail distribution reliability
standards established by the Commission's reliability rulemaking at Docket No. L-00970120 dated April
23, 1998, 52 Pa. Code § 57.191-57.198, as well as any other future Commission reliability directives
affecting FE’s retail customers. Adherence to those standards and the terms of this 2022 Consolidated
Agreement, including the IDI and IFI Standards defined in Paragraph 9 below, is expected to allow FE to
operate and maintain its transmission and distribution systems as part of its continuing commitment to
improve system reliability for all retail and wholesale customers.
2. This settlement agreement shall not be construed to modify the terms of the JPP, as
amended and restated, or any other terms and conditions of the 2014 Consolidated Agreement and 2014
Extension Agreement, as modified, unless specifically provided in this settlement agreement. The
Parties agree that the terms of the JPP, the 2014 Consolidated Agreement, the 2014 Extension
Agreement, and all other terms and conditions of agreements between the Parties, have been fully
captured and are accurately contained within this currently effective 2022 Consolidated Agreement,
effective upon the date that FERC accepts this 2022 Consolidated Agreement for filing.
3. The Parties agree that compliance with the provisions of this 2022 Consolidated
Agreement is subject to the existing enforcement rights in the JPP, as most recently restated in the 2014
Consolidated Agreement and 2014 Extension Agreement and as restated herein.
4. For the period of the effective date of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement through
December 31, 2032, PREA/AEC agrees that it shall not intervene in any proceeding filed by FE or its
subsidiaries before the PaPUC, including but not limited to proceedings pertaining to rate changes, long
term infrastructure improvement plans, distribution system improvement charges, change of control or
ownership, and certificates of public convenience (unless such certificate of public convenience or change
of control filings involve the full or partial acquisition of one or more member cooperatives or a
cooperative's service territory), except that PREA/AEC may intervene in any such proceeding or filings
in which FE or its subsidiaries otherwise propose changes in their operational terms and conditions of
service under which one or more PREA/AEC member cooperatives are receiving service or are otherwise
directly impacted. PREA/AEC retains its right to intervene in any PaPUC-initiated investigations or to
initiate a complaint on PREA/AEC's own behalf or to intervene in any proceedings initiated by parties
other than FE.
5. Extending the JPP process as defined herein means extending all parts of the JPP currently
in effect on the date hereof, as it may be subsequently amended by the mutual agreement of the Parties,
through the end of the JPP process as agreed upon herein.
6. FE also confirms that the former AE's consent is not required and that FE shall be bound,
to the extent necessary to achieve the goals of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement, to include and perform
the requirements of the JPP on FE's West Penn system.
7. All of the foregoing recitals, including the various agreements referenced therein, are
incorporated into, and are an integral part of, the terms of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement to the extent
4
they remain in effect. Notwithstanding anything herein to the contrary, this 2022 Consolidated Agreement
is not intended to supersede or nullify any of the prior orders or agreements which contain the provisions
noted herein. This 2022 Consolidated Agreement synthesizes those prior orders and agreements for clarity
and ease of reference and shall be the reference point for all questions related to the JPP. In case of a
conflict between a provision of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement and a provision of a prior order or
agreement, which provision has not been superseded by time or a subsequent agreement, the provision(s)
of the prior order or agreement shall control.
8. This 2022 Consolidated Agreement intentionally does not contain provisions which are
expired or otherwise no longer applicable to the relationship between the parties.
B. PREA/AEC – FE Reliability Standards
9. The following Interruption Duration Index (“IDI”) and Interruption Frequency Index
(“IFI”) Standards (collectively, “Standards”) apply for purposes of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement, as
approved by the Commission1
:

10. For purposes of measuring the outage period for the IFI/IDI standards and for compiling
outage data as required by Paragraph 23 below, for any delivery point that can be restored to service from
an energized PREA/AEC member cooperative delivery point, the duration of an outage will be calculated
as the amount of time starting with the time the FE outage began and ending at the time that: 1) electric
service is restored to 90% of the consumers served by the delivery point through back feeding by the
PREA/AEC member cooperative; or 2) by restoration of the FE service to the outaged delivery point,
1 A sustained outage is defined as an outage with a duration in excess of five minutes.
5
whichever occurs first. Verification of the restoration of the consumers will be accomplished with the
PREA/AEC member cooperative outage reports and the energy consumption records from the meters for
the delivery points involved.
11. In providing to PREA/AEC the outage data as required by Paragraph 23, FE will identify
outages caused by the specific events listed below in subparagraphs (i) though (v):
(i) Immediately resulting from a motor vehicle coming in contact with a transmission or
distribution line pole or other facility on the circuit currently serving the delivery point
at the time of the occurrence, or on FE’s associated source of supply for the circuit
currently serving the delivery point;
(ii) Directly caused by a tornado on the circuit currently serving the delivery point where
a National Weather Service Investigation has verified the occurrence of a tornado, or
due to a verified tornado’s damage on FE’s associated source of supply for the circuit
currently serving the delivery point;
(iii)Directly caused by a tree being felled by a third party not affiliated with FE, its affiliates
or its agents/contractors in the course of performing tree-related work for FE, onto FE’s
facilities serving the delivery point or FE’s associated source of supply for the circuit
currently serving the delivery point;
(iv)Directly caused by an icing event that deposits ¾ of an inch of radial ice or more, which
occurrence is verified by the affected local member cooperative(s) or independent
recognized source; or
(v) Directly caused by a non-preventable tree located outside FE’s right-of-way in the
Allegheny National Forest or State Forest/Gamelands in Pennsylvania (limited to those
areas specifically identified in Appendix B attached hereto) falling into a 115 kV or
higher voltage source of supply. Such occurrence, location (by pole number) and cause
shall be provided to PREA/AEC within a reasonable time.
12. a. In accordance with Paragraph E.4. of the Restructuring Agreement dated
September 23, 1998, the reliability performance of the PREA/AEC delivery points measured against the
IDI and IFI Standards outlined in Paragraph 9 will be included in a report to be filed by FE with the
Commission and provided to PREA/AEC by March 31st. This report is in addition to any other reports
that FE may be required to file with the Commission reporting on the reliability of service provided to its
retail customers.
b. The Parties will meet periodically, but at least quarterly to review any delivery
points where the IDI and IFI Standards are not met during the previous quarter, and determine how
to address any system deficiencies. Any matters not resolved between Parties shall be presented
to the Commission’s Chairman’s office or his/her Commission delegate for resolution through
nonbinding mediation, pursuant to the procedures outlined in Paragraph 25 below, within 120 days
of the filing of such report as described in Paragraph 12.a.
6
C. Joint Planning Process
13. It is agreed that the JPP established in Commission Docket Nos. R-00974008 and R00974009 and as amended by subsequent proceedings and settlement, in which representatives of the
Parties, and a consumer representative, if it so desires to participate, will continue through the 2032
planning year (for 2033 construction). The purpose of the JPP is to develop annual calendar year plans for
allocation of FE expenditures for specific projects devoted to circuits that improve service reliability to
PREA/AEC delivery points.
The JPP will be followed each year in order to develop appropriate projects to improve reliability
at PREA/AEC delivery points.
a. During the first quarter of each calendar year, PREA/AEC will transmit to FE a
preliminary list of delivery points2
to be addressed by the JPP from which improvement projects
will be developed for construction or implementation in the following calendar year. In developing
the list of investment targets, PREA/AEC shall use reasonable efforts to include projects that are
at a cost of no less than $250,000 in any given project year. The Parties will meet to exchange
information3
and generally discuss FE's service reliability in relation to PREA/AEC delivery
points. The information provided by the Parties shall include adequate and sufficient information
to allow the Parties to facilitate the JPP in a timely and efficient manner.
b. During the second quarter of each year after receipt of FE's input on PREA/AEC’s
preliminary list of suggested projects and associated costs (which receipt shall be no later than
April 30), PREA/AEC will provide to FE a list of suggested projects and costs to improve
reliability to cooperative delivery points no later than May 31st.
c. By June 30th of each year, the Parties will meet in good faith to discuss and attempt
to resolve expeditiously any differences regarding the implementation of the list of projects.
d. By July 31st of each year, PREA/AEC shall designate a final list of projects and
associated costs "PREA/AEC Final List" to be completed in the following calendar year. If FE
disputes the inclusion of a project (and associated costs) in the PREA/AEC Final List, FE has the
right to bring that disputed project(s) to the Commission's Chairman's office or his delegate for
resolution through binding arbitration during the third quarter of each year but shall expeditiously
pursue completion of the undisputed projects. If FE fails to raise any dispute as provided herein
during the third quarter, the PREA/AEC Final List shall become the final JPP for that year in its
entirety.
14. FE commits to invest at least the following annual expenditure amounts that will be the
2 Delivery points as defined in the 1993 Wheeling and Supplemental Power Agreement, or any subsequent or successor wheeling or
interconnection agreements or subsequent amendments to these agreements.
3 Both FE and PREA/AEC shall enter into Confidentiality Agreements as necessary to protect any sensitive information.
7
subject of the JPP process specifically to improve or upgrade the reliability of FE’s systems serving
PREA/AEC delivery points.
a. For planning year 2022 (for 2023 construction projects), the investment level will
be $6 million per year, and will cover all FE systems serving PREA/AEC member cooperative
delivery points.
b. Of the amounts that FE is committing to expend for planning year 2022 (for 2023
construction projects), no more than $75,000 per year shall be permitted to be retained to offset
the expenses of administering this 2022 Consolidated Agreement and the JPP.
c. For the five-year extension period beginning in 2023 (for 2024 construction
projects through 2028 construction projects, “2022 Extension Projects”), the annual investment
will be $8 million; for the subsequent five-year extension period beginning in 2028 (for 2029-
2033 construction projects), the annual investment will be $10 million.
d. Of the amounts that FE is committing to expend each year beginning in planning
year 2023 (for 2024 construction projects), no more than $100,000 per year shall be permitted to
be retained to offset the expenses of administering this 2022 Consolidated Agreement and the
JPP.
e. For all investment commitments included in subparagraphs 14.a. and 14.c. above,
the dollars will be allocated to cover all FE systems serving PREA/AEC member cooperative
delivery points, as defined by each Interconnection Agreement for Wholesale Load as in place
for all PREA/AEC Pennsylvania-situated delivery points.
f. The annual investment levels for the 2023-2032 planning period (for 2024-2033
construction year projects) shall be maintained, without reduction, regardless of reliability
performance to any of the PREA/AEC delivery points.
g. The portion of the investment committed for each construction year that shall be
spent on operations and maintenance activities are: $1.5 million for 2023-2028; and $2 million
for 2029-2033 construction years.
15. In connection with each final project constructed under Paragraph 14, above, FE will also
provide the total actual expenditures incurred in connection with each project initiated under the JPP
outlined therein. Actual expenditures will be provided in March of each year to PREA/AEC, reflecting
actual expenditures incurred on each project on the prior year's JPP project list. Actual expenditures will
also be provided monthly, reflecting year-to-date actual expenditures on each project on the current
year's JPP project list. The Parties agree that, if the annual actual expenditures provided in March are
greater than or less than the designated per year expenditures specified in Paragraph 14, above, there
will be a corresponding reduction or increase respectively reflected in the following year's required level
of expenditures.
8
16. The Parties will schedule a meeting to be held before December 31, 2030, at which the
Parties will meet in good faith to discuss extending the JPP beyond planning year 2032 and to consider
whether revisions to the JPP are necessary. Nothing in this provision is intended to be construed as a
commitment by FE for continued or increased funding beyond planning year 2032 (for construction year
2033).
D. Inspections
17. The Parties have agreed that the following will constitute satisfactory inspection of wood
poles on all FE circuits, regardless of voltage, serving PREA/AEC delivery points:
a. For each such circuit serving a PREA/AEC delivery point, regardless of voltage,
FE, its affiliates and/or its agents/contractors will perform a "full inspection," consistent with the
FE "Guidelines for Inspection and Treatment of Transmission Wood Poles," (attached hereto as
Appendix A). This inspection shall be inclusive of each pole (including lateral taps that are not
sectionalized from the normal source of supply for the delivery point) from the substation to and
including the first FE-owned automated switching device beyond the PREA/AEC delivery point
("Serving Poles") on each circuit that serves as the normal source of supply to PREA/AEC delivery
points. This work will be performed on a ten-year cycle so that each Serving Pole is fully inspected
every ten years.
b. A full inspection shall include an inspection and a report of the inspection findings
("Inspection Report") performed in strict accordance with Appendix A and the definitions included
therein.
c. FE shall take the following actions upon receipt of Inspection Reports: (i) Priority
One poles shall be replaced within 60 days; (ii) Reinforceable Priority Poles shall be reinforced or
replaced within 180 days; (iii) Non-Reinforceable Priority Poles shall be replaced within 120 days;
and (iv) other reliability items will be corrected promptly in accordance with reasonable and
prudent industry standards, but in no event longer than twelve months after being reported.
18. FE, its affiliates, or its pole inspection agents/contractors will provide copies of all of the
Inspection Reports specified in Appendix A hereto for the Serving Poles to PREA/AEC (electronically, if
available) on a quarterly basis. These reports shall be used only for the purpose of verifying compliance
with Paragraph 17 hereof and other settlement requirements.
19. FE will maintain itsinspection and maintenance practices for radio-controlled line switches
and reclosers consistent with industry practice to include a program that requires the replacement of the
batteries on radio-controlled switches and reclosers on no more than a three-year cycle. To the extent that
the manufacturer's specifications allow, the batteries installed will have no less than an 8 ampere-hour
service rating. In addition, FE will at least semi-annually inspect and maintain all radio controlledswitches and reclosers on circuits serving PREA/AEC delivery points, which inspection will include, but
not be limited to, a load test on the batteries and a confirmation of the connectivity of the radio control to
FE's Regional Dispatch Office (“RDO”). Manual switches will be inspected annually. FE will take timely
9
action to correct problems found as a result of the inspections and tests under this Paragraph, but in no
event longer than twelve months after being reported.
20. FE shall repair or replace any failed meter or component within 90 days after becoming
aware of such failed meter or component, unless extenuating circumstances beyond FE's control prevent
FE from being able to repair or replace the meter or component within 90 days provided that FE shall
promptly notify PREA/AEC of any such extenuating circumstances and keep PREA/AEC advised of the
situation until the meter or component has been successfully repaired or replaced.
21. The existing "auto-dialer" system for all FE-served delivery points to detect and
communicate to FE's RDO loss of potential on any of the three phases serving a PREA/AEC delivery
point will be eliminated, with this function to be filled by FE’s transmission, sub-transmission, and
distribution supervisory control and data acquisition (“SCADA”) or other automated monitoring and
notification systems paired with communications from PREA/AEC member cooperatives to confirm
losses of power. Elimination of the “auto-dialer” system will be accomplished on a delivery point-bydelivery point basis, with elimination subject to written confirmation that FE’s SCADA or other automated
monitoring and notification system clearly identifies and contains fully functioning processes to alert,
notify, and alarm the system operators of any outage or system variance condition impacting full three
phase service to PREA/AEC delivery points. All PREA/AEC delivery points will remain Priority 1
customers across the FE PA system for restoration purposes, and the SCADA monitoring systems shall
clearly identify the delivery points as such.
E. Joint Operations/Engineering Review Committee
22. The Joint Operations/Engineering Review ("JO/ER") Committee, consisting of a limited
number of appropriate personnel from each entity familiar with the respective distribution and
transmission systems, will meet periodically, but at least monthly, to:
a. discuss specific and system-wide engineering and operational issues.
b. if requested by PREA/AEC, discuss any major event, as defined in the Commission
reliability regulations,4
affecting PREA/AEC delivery points within fifteen days of the conclusion
of the major event.
c. review the reports required under this 2022 Consolidated Agreement.
d. discuss criteria for recommending eligible projects under the JPP to be undertaken
by FE to improve reliability to PREA/AEC delivery points. The JO/ER Committee may also
participate in developing criteria for recommending eligible projects to be undertaken under any
Reliability Improvement Plan (“RIP”) to be developed pursuant to Paragraph 24 of this 2022
Consolidated Agreement.
4 For purposes of implementing the existing JPP, major event shall be interpreted as defined in the then-current Commission reliability
regulations.
10
e. develop operating procedures/protocols under which FE’s dispatching staff will
accept information from certain mutually agreed-upon member cooperative personnel relating to
outage issues and act on that information to restore service as promptly and as safely as possible.
f. discuss any specific outages of concern to the member cooperatives served from
FE’s 34.5 kV or lower circuits occurring during the quarter to the extent PREA/AEC continues to
have concerns and to review all outages on FE’s 46 kV and above transmission circuits and the
steps FE is undertaking to prevent a recurrence of those outages.
g. review the battery load test results and the connectivity of the radio controls
conducted under Paragraph 19, above.
23. FE will provide within thirty days from the end of each calendar quarter (a) detail for each
outage event, by delivery point, which shall include the start time, duration, end time, and cause of the
interruption; and (b) an electronic spreadsheet providing rankings (worst to best) of all PREA/AEC
delivery points based on: (i) IDI; (ii) IFI; and (iii) consumer minutes of outage using the number of
member cooperative consumers served by each delivery point, both including and excluding major events.
PREA/AEC will determine the top 20% of PREA/AEC delivery points, from these combined lists,
excluding major events, to be designated as the PREA/AEC worst performing delivery points for that
quarter (“Worst Performing Delivery Points”). The JO/ER will review the Worst Performing Delivery
Points as well as other delivery points designated by PREA/AEC that experienced significant interruptions
in service and mutually determine whether a RIP is necessary.
24. When a RIP is necessary, a physical field assessment will be conducted by an FE engineer
and such other FE personnel as is appropriate. The JO/ER Committee will then develop a mutually
agreeable RIP. Such RIP will include a description of the work/actions to be completed and a schedule for
completion of the work/actions which will address and remedy the causes for the poor performances on
the delivery points. Such RIPs will be timely implemented by FE and the fact that the RIP will result in
FE incurring a cost is not in and of itself justification for not timely implementing the RIP.
If the JO/ER is not able to mutually agree to the requisite RIP within 90 days of the end of any
calendar quarter, then PREA/AEC has the right to seek Commission mediation as set forth in Section III.E
of the Restructuring Settlement dated September 23, 1998, and as restated in Paragraph 25, below.
During the term of the JPP, any JO/ER RIPs developed may be considered on a timely basis within
the JPP process, however, in no event are the JPP projects limited to these RIPs.
25. Any matters not resolved between Parties shall be presented to the Commission’s
Chairman’s office or his/her Commission delegate for resolution through nonbinding mediation in an
expeditious manner. If PREA/AEC’s satisfaction is not achieved through mediation, then a formal
complaint may be filed by PREA/AEC with the Commission seeking to establish its entitlement to a
satisfactory RIP to be implemented in a timeframe acceptable to PREA/AEC. The Commission agrees to
resolve any formal complaint(s) within 120 days of the complaint(s) being served upon FE. Should the
result of the complaint process be the adoption of findings adverse to FE, the scope of remedies the
Commission may consider include, but are not limited to, a determination that the ongoing expenditures
11
by FE that impact reliability to the PREA/AEC delivery points should be increased. The costs of these
RIPs are not to be included in the funding required in Paragraph 14 above. This 2022 Consolidated
Agreement does not bar or limit in any way FE's entitlement to present legal and/or factual argument to
the Commission as a defense against such complaints presented by PREA/AEC. Specifically, FE does not
waive its right to challenge the legality of Commission jurisdiction over complaints filed by PREA/AEC
alleging lack of adequate or reliable service.
F. Prioritization of Restoration
26. FE will maintain the PREA/AEC delivery points at a restoration priority equal to the loads
listed below. Specifically, other than delivery points served at 115 kV or above, which shall have a higher
priority, PREA/AEC delivery points are designated “Priority One Customers” (or such equivalent FE
classification) and have priority with respect to the restoration of service equal to any of the following
retail customers:
Hospitals
Critical life support customers
Telephone exchanges
Water supply and pumping stations
Sewage treatment systems
Police departments
Fire departments
Correctional institutions
Radio and TV stations and newspapers
The number of cooperative consumers served through each PREA/AEC delivery point will be
incorporated in the FE outage management system, GIS, and taken into consideration during restoration
activities. PREA/AEC will provide FE, on an annual basis, the number of cooperative consumers served
through each PREA/AEC delivery point, including the number and nature of any critical cooperative
loads, and will promptly provide an interim report to FE of any known significant changes in customer
load that occur during an annual period.
27. Refresher training shall be conducted at least annually for FE dispatching, engineering,
operations, and service center personnel to ensure that those personnel are aware of the names, geographic
location, upstream substations and sectionalizing devices serving/protecting PREA/AEC delivery points,
as well as the number of consumers served by each delivery point. FE’s call center personnel will be
trained regarding the names and geographical locations of the PREA/AEC delivery points as well as the
number of consumers served through those delivery points.
28. Throughout the term of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement, any disputes concerning FE’s
commitments under this 2022 Consolidated Agreement pertaining to PREA/AEC delivery points shall be
subject to the mediation process set forth in Section III.E of the Restructuring Agreement dated September
23, 1998, and as restated in Paragraph 25, herein. This remedy is in addition to, and not in substitution for,
the other remedies provided in this 2022 Consolidated Agreement.
12
G. Termination of WASP Agreements
29. Termination of the WASP Agreements will require that FE submit to FERC (a) notices of
termination of the WASP Agreements and (b) four new interconnection agreements between AEC and,
respectively, FE subsidiaries Penelec, Met-Ed, JCP&L, and MAIT.
30. The interconnection agreements between AEC and FE establish the terms and conditions
for the interconnection and coordinated operation of the Parties’ systems and for AEC’s use of certain
distribution facilities to enable AEC to serve its wholesale loads. In addition, the Penelec and Met-Ed
interconnection agreements each establish rates for wholesale distribution service taken over distributionvoltage facilities owned and operated by each of those two FE subsidiaries. The rates identified in
Appendix 1 of the Penelec and Met-Ed interconnection agreements are inclusive of any costs associated
with metering equipment referenced in the interconnection agreements that are not included in
transmission rates approved by FERC.
31. FE shall timely submit to FERC notices of termination and interconnection agreements,
